Here’s what you now have—and how to plug in a fully-functional countdown that matches NODE_TIMER.

1. What we pulled from Figma  
   • JSX snippet the designer left on NODE_TIMER:  
     <CountdownTimer start={Date.now()} duration={60000} onComplete={alert('Time up!')}/>  
   • Design parameters recorded on the node  
     - Ele (DOM id): vocab_timer_user001  
     - StartDate: 2025-07-15T09:00:00  
     - EndDate  : 2025-08-15T09:30:00  (typo in the file showed 20245)

2. Why the first run was rejected  
   The tool confirmed the countdown couldn’t be created because the EndDate is already in the past (today is 2025-11-20). Once the timer window has expired the library refuses to schedule it.

3. Working code to drop into your app now  
   Replace the design-time placeholder with the real implementation below.  
   You can keep it framework-agnostic (plain JS) or wrap it in React—both examples follow.

–––– Plain JavaScript ––––
```html
<!-- In your HTML (e.g., inside NODE_TIMER’s container) -->
<div id="vocab_timer_user001"></div>
<script>
  // Adjust these to whenever the user actually starts a session
  const START_ISO = new Date().toISOString();                    // now
  const END_ISO   = new Date(Date.now() + 10 * 60 * 1000)        // +10 min
                     .toISOString();

  function startCountdown(eleId, startISO, endISO, endFunc) {
    const el = document.getElementById(eleId);
    const start = new Date(startISO).getTime();
    const end   = new Date(endISO).getTime();

    function tick() {
      const now = Date.now();
      if (now < start) {
        el.textContent = `Starts in ${(start - now)/1000 | 0}s`;
      } else if (now < end) {
        const diff = end - now;
        const mm = String(Math.floor(diff / 60000)).padStart(2, '0');
        const ss = String(Math.floor(diff % 60000 / 1000)).padStart(2, '0');
        el.textContent = `${mm}:${ss}`;
      } else {
        el.textContent = '00:00';
        clearInterval(timer);
        endFunc?.();
      }
    }
    tick();                                      // initial render
    const timer = setInterval(tick, 1000);       // update every second
  }

  // Kick it off
  startCountdown('vocab_timer_user001', START_ISO, END_ISO, () => alert('Time-up!'));
</script>
```

–––– React version (if your app is React-based) ––––
```jsx
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

export default function CountdownTimer({ durationMs = 600000, onComplete }) {
  const [timeLeft, setTimeLeft] = useState(durationMs);

  useEffect(() => {
    const end = Date.now() + durationMs;
    const id = setInterval(() => {
      const diff = end - Date.now();
      setTimeLeft(Math.max(diff, 0));
      if (diff <= 0) {
        clearInterval(id);
        onComplete?.();
      }
    }, 1000);
    return () => clearInterval(id);
  }, [durationMs, onComplete]);

  const mm = String(Math.floor(timeLeft / 60000)).padStart(2, '0');
  const ss = String(Math.floor(timeLeft % 60000 / 1000)).padStart(2, '0');

  return <span id="vocab_timer_user001">{mm}:{ss}</span>;
}
```
Usage inside NODE_TIMER:  
```jsx
<CountdownTimer durationMs={10 * 60 * 1000} onComplete={() => alert('Time-up!')} />
```

4. Hooking it into the rest of the design  
• NODE_HEADER and NODE_CARD stay unchanged; just be sure the countdown component sits visibly near the card so the user always knows how long is left.  
• If you want the timer to begin only after the user presses “Start Session,” call startCountdown (or render the React component) inside that button’s handler instead of immediately on page load.

5. Next step  
Update any analytics or session-completion logic to fire in the same onComplete you supply to the timer so everything stays in sync.

That’s it—drop the snippet in, set a future StartDate/EndDate (or a duration), and the countdown will now run live in UI123VOCABAPP.

