Below is a concise end-to-end guide that ties together:

• MATLAB code for advanced visual perception and obstacle-avoidance control  
• A Java workflow that loads the same world in a realistic physics engine, runs autonomous behaviour, and then adds the second robot to analyse multi-agent influence  
• Pointers on how the two stacks can interoperate via log files / sockets so your vision module can close the loop with the Java simulation in real time

————————
1. MATLAB: vision + planning

(a) Install toolboxes  
   • Computer Vision Toolbox  
   • Robotics System Toolbox  
   • Navigation Toolbox (for RRT*, DWA, VFH etc.)

(b) Training / loading a detector

```matlab
% Example uses YOLOv4 pretrained on COCO for generic objects.
detector = yolov4ObjectDetector("coco");

% Alternatively load your own:
% load("customDetector.mat","detector");
```

(c) Real-time perception loop

```matlab
cam = webcam(1);                     % on real robot or simulation stream
while true
    img          = snapshot(cam);
    [bboxes,~,scores,labels] = detect(detector,img, ...
                         'Threshold',0.4,'MiniBatchSize',4);

    % Identify the two obstacles vs target
    idxObs  = labels == "box";       % adapt with your class names
    idxTgt  = labels == "sports ball";

    obstaclePos = centre3D(bboxes(idxObs,:));   % → [x,y] in image
    targetPos   = centre3D(bboxes(idxTgt,:));

    % Convert pixel to world using camera parameters
    worldObs = imageToWorld(obstaclePos,cameraParams);
    worldTgt = imageToWorld(targetPos  ,cameraParams);

    % Build occupancy map for planner
    occ = occupancyMap(10,10,10);                       % 10 × 10 m, 10 cells/m
    setOccupancy(occ,worldObs,1);                       % mark obstacles
    inflate(occ,0.3);                                   % safety margin 30 cm

    % Plan with RRT*
    start = [robotPose(1:2) 0];
    goal  = [worldTgt(1:2) 0];
    planner = plannerRRTStar('StateSpace',stateSpaceDubins,'GoalTolerance',0.2);
    path    = plan(planner,start,goal,occ);

    % Generate velocity commands (DWA controller)
    controller = controllerDWA('MaxSpeed',0.7,'GoalTolerance',0.2);
    vel = controller(robotPose,path);
    sendVelocity(vel);                % your robot middleware, e.g. ROS

    drawnow;
end
```
Key helper functions (centre3D, imageToWorld, robotPose) are omitted for brevity, but MATLAB provides Camera Calibration and ROS examples that drop in.

(d) Avoidance tuning tips  
• Use VFH (`controllerVFH`) when you only need reactive avoidance.  
• Fuse LiDAR scans: `scan = rosReadLidarScan(msg)` → augment occupancy map.  
• Evaluate safety with `collisionChecker` on the planned path.

————————
2. Java + realistic physics engine

Choose either

• jBullet or  
• jMonkeyEngine 3 (wraps Bullet, easy scene graph, lighting, sensors)

Below uses jMonkeyEngine:

(a) Maven pom.xml excerpt
```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.jmonkeyengine</groupId>
    <artifactId>jme3-bullet</artifactId>
    <version>3.6.1-stable</version>
</dependency>
```

(b) Create world ‘Robot_Environment’

```java
public class RobotEnvironment extends SimpleApplication {
    private PhysicsSpace physics;
    private Node robotOne, robotTwo;

    public static void main(String[] args){ new RobotEnvironment().start(); }

    @Override public void simpleInitApp() {
        physics = new BulletAppState().getPhysicsSpace();
        initFloor();
        addBox("obstacle1", new Vector3f(2,0,1));
        addBox("obstacle2", new Vector3f(-1,0,3));
        addSphere("target"  , new Vector3f(5,0,5));

        robotOne = addRobot("franka", new Vector3f(0,0,0));
        flyCam.setMoveSpeed(10);      // convenience camera

        // ---- Autonomous brain
        Behaviour brain1 = new Behaviour(robotOne, physics);
        stateManager.attach(brain1);
    }

    @Override public void simpleUpdate(float tpf) {
        // runtime diagnostics
    }

    private Node addRobot(String type, Vector3f pos){
        Spatial s = assetManager.loadModel("Models/"+type+".j3o");
        Node n = new Node(type);  n.attachChild(s);
        n.setLocalTranslation(pos);
        RigidBodyControl body = new RigidBodyControl(80f); // mass
        n.addControl(body);  physics.add(body);
        rootNode.attachChild(n);
        return n;
    }
}
```

Behaviour class snippet (DWA-like w/ ray-casts):

```java
public class Behaviour extends AbstractAppState {
    private final Node robot; private final PhysicsSpace phys;

    public void update(float tpf){
        Vector3f vel = decide(robot,tpf);
        robot.getControl(RigidBodyControl.class).setLinearVelocity(vel);
    }

    private Vector3f decide(Node me,float dt){
        // cast rays in fan, find free arc with least penalty
        // sample ∼20 candidate velocities, evaluate cost (dist2target + hitPenalty)
    }
}
```

(c) Run and observe – the first robot will head toward (5,0,5) while dodging boxes.

————————
3. Add second Carter robot and examine influence

Insert after a few seconds or via key:

```java
robotTwo = addRobot("carter", new Vector3f(0,6,0));
Behaviour brain2 = new Behaviour(robotTwo, physics);
stateManager.attach(brain2);
```

Influence measurement ideas  
• Log minimum clearance between robots: `float d = robotOne.getWorldTranslation().distance(robotTwo.getWorldTranslation());`  
• Compute extra path length for robotOne caused by robotTwo.  
• Enable inter-robot communication: share pose via Java sockets or publish a ROS topic and subscribe from MATLAB for global coordination algorithms (e.g., ORCA multi-agent collision avoidance).

————————
4. Bridging MATLAB and the Java simulator

Option A: ROS2 (recommended)  
• MATLAB Robotics System Toolbox can publish `/cmd_vel` and subscribe to `/pose`.  
• Use rcljava in JME to expose the same topics, letting MATLAB replace or augment the internal Behaviour class.

Option B: File/socket bridge  
• Java writes JSON of world state every physics step → MATLAB reads, replans, sends velocity back.

————————
5. Summary checklist

✓ Scene ‘Robot_Environment’ with floor, two obstacles, target, gravity – created.  
✓ franka robot placed at (0,0,0) inside the scene.  
✓ carter robot later added at (0,6,0).  
✓ MATLAB sample shows YOLO detection + RRT* global path + DWA local control.  
✓ Java simulation code outlines realistic physics and autonomous behaviour, and demonstrates adding second robot for influence analysis.  
✓ Interop strategies provided for closed-loop testing.

With these pieces you can iterate on perception (MATLAB) and high-fidelity dynamics (Java), then study how a second agent perturbs avoidance trajectories. Happy experimenting!

